I often wonder if millennials might be the last generation able to appreciate art purely and connect with artists. We don't have that pressure; we don't need to view everything through critical glasses.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but that collective consciousness has disappeared now.
Back then, we could immerse ourselves directly in content without considering its origins, because tracing back then was not easy.
We revered these artists like gods, and there was no reason to question this worship. So we established a "pseudo-social relationship" with them, seeing it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so enchanted by nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together while eating pizza.
This experience differs starkly from how we now consume shows via streaming platforms. Platforms typically release 12 episodes at once, allowing viewers to watch at their own pace, and users post about plot points on social media with a "spoiler alert," or they confine discussions to specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all yearn for the sense of collective belonging that tied everyone together.
It is precisely this nostalgia that compels us to revisit series like "The Office" or movies like "Airplane!" time and again, with memorable lines from these works circulating online like memes.
We quote these classic lines from the shows among ourselves, believing most people will understand the references.
Now, even if something goes viral online, we can no longer take for granted that everyone has seen it.
With information exploding, there's so much we need to pay attention to that it's impossible to simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape this state of information overload?
We discover new media and new artists again and again, only to find they are either notorious sex abusers or stubbornly biased individuals, and this cycle is exhausting.
On one hand, we indulge in nostalgia, while on the other, we must acknowledge that the people who created the art we love may have serious moral flaws, leaving us at a loss.
We will be more cautious in establishing "social-like" relationships with artists.
We gradually realize that if someone wants to achieve wealth and power, it becomes difficult to ensure they will not harm others or exploit them.
With the collective consciousness of the media no longer present, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Naturally, there are still some people who remain obsessed, eager to elevate others to godlike status only to be shocked when the idol falls.
We are living in a time of change, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
